# Coverage closure ({{ ip }}, phase 5)

## Precondition

Phase 4 done: the regression runs clean (`make -C sim matrix` CLEAN for the
target configurations). See `triage-regression.prompt.md`.

## Goal

Analyze functional coverage holes, extend covergroups/tests to close them,
and iterate until the coverage goals are met for EVERY configuration.

## Relevant files

{% for a in agents %}
* `env/{{ ip }}_{{ a.name }}_coverage.sv` — '{{ a.name }}' covergroup (`{{ a.name }}_cg`); replace the
  example coverpoints with the real plan, add crosses
{% endfor %}
* `seq_lib/`, `tests/` — new stimulus targeting specific holes
* `cfg/*.yaml` — some bins only exist under certain parameter sets; use the
  `params` map / `prm_*` mirrors in `{{ ip }}_env_cfg` to guard config-dependent
  bins (`ignore_bins` what a configuration cannot hit)

## Procedure

1. Run the regression with coverage collection, e.g.
   `make -C sim regress XRUN_OPTS="-coverage all -covoverwrite"` (or add the
   site's coverage flags), then merge/inspect with IMC.
2. Rank holes: protocol-critical first; mark unreachable-by-configuration
   bins with `ignore_bins` + a comment naming the parameter condition.
3. For each real hole: extend an existing sequence or add a directed one,
   register any new test in `sim/{{ vsif_name }}`, re-run.
4. Repeat per configuration: `make -C sim regress CFG=cfg/<config>.yaml` —
   coverage percentages recorded in `verif_matrix.yaml` when present in logs.

## Rules

* A hole is closed by STIMULUS or justified by a documented exclusion — never
  by deleting the coverpoint.
* Coverage code must stay config-aware: never write bins that silently can't
  hit under a shipping configuration.

## Done when

Coverage goals are met (or exclusions documented) for every configuration in
`cfg/`. Then continue with `verif-closure.prompt.md`.
